00:02:20.360 --> 00:02:24.300
So if you live in China, and you need some
ivory to make the handle for a sword, you

00:02:24.300 --> 00:02:29.000
have to trade for it, because elephants only
live in India and Africa. One of the reasons

00:02:29.000 --> 00:02:33.910
Indian Ocean trade took off is that there
were a wide range of resources available and

00:02:33.910 --> 00:02:39.280
a wide range of import needs -- from ivory
to timber to books to grain. But the most

00:02:39.280 --> 00:02:41.420
important thing was the wind.

00:02:41.420 --> 00:02:45.840
The Indian Ocean is home to a set of very
special winds called Monsoons. You generally

00:02:45.840 --> 00:02:50.250
hear about Monsoons in the context of rain
in India, but rather than thinking of Monsoons

00:02:50.250 --> 00:02:55.460
as the rain itself, think of them as the wind
that bring a rainy season. The great thing

00:02:55.460 --> 00:02:59.960
about seasons is that they come regularly
-- and so do the Monsoon winds. So if you

00:02:59.960 --> 00:03:05.160
were a sailor, you could count on the wind
to bring you from Africa to India if you sailed

00:03:05.160 --> 00:03:09.240
between April and September, and one that
would bring you back to Africa if you sailed

00:03:09.240 --> 00:03:14.340
between November and February. In fact, these
winds were so predictable that early maritime

00:03:14.340 --> 00:03:20.300
travel guides often listed ideal times of 
down to the week and sometimes even the day.

00:03:20.300 --> 00:03:24.060
Predictable winds make trade a lot less risky:
Like, back in the day when the only power

00:03:24.070 --> 00:03:29.260
for ships were sails and oarsmen, your cargo
might not arrive on time, or it might spoil,

00:03:29.260 --> 00:03:34.480
or you might die, all of which are bad for
the health of global economic trade. But predictable

00:03:34.480 --> 00:03:39.890
winds meant lower risk, which meant cheaper
trade, which meant more trade, which meant

00:03:39.890 --> 00:03:42.830
more people could have awesome sword handles.
Thanks Thought Bubble.

00:03:42.830 --> 00:03:46.320
Okay, there are a few more facets of Indian
Ocean trade worth mentioning. First, Indian

00:03:46.320 --> 00:03:51.210
Ocean trade incorporated many more people
than participated in Silk Road trade. There

00:03:51.210 --> 00:03:55.470
were Jewish people and people from Africa
to Malaysia and India and China, all sailing

00:03:55.470 --> 00:03:59.060
around and setting up trading communities
where they would act as middle men, trying

00:03:59.060 --> 00:04:04.040
to sell stuff for more than they bought it for and trying
to find new stuff to buy that they could sell later.

00:04:04.040 --> 00:04:07.040
But despite this diversity, for the most part,
especially on the Western half of the Indian

00:04:07.040 --> 00:04:11.350
Ocean basin, the trade was dominated by Muslim
merchants. Why? Largely because they had the

00:04:11.350 --> 00:04:15.320
money to build ships, although we will see
that in the 15th century, the Chinese state

00:04:15.320 --> 00:04:18.100
could have changed that balance completely.
By the way, I need to point out that when

00:04:18.100 --> 00:04:21.810
I say that the trade was dominated by Muslim
merchants, the emphasis should be on the merchants-

00:04:21.810 --> 00:04:23.900
not the Muslim or the dominated.

00:04:23.900 --> 00:04:27.190
As previously noted, we tend to think that
states and governments and the funny-hatted

00:04:27.190 --> 00:04:31.060
people who rule them are the real movers and
shakers in history, but that’s really not

00:04:31.060 --> 00:04:34.340
the case. In the Indian Ocean, the terms of
trade were set by the merchants and by the

00:04:34.340 --> 00:04:38.190
demands of the market, not by the whims of
political rulers. And the self-regulating

00:04:38.190 --> 00:04:42.320
nature of that trade was remarkable and pretty
much unprecedented. I mean, the most amazing

00:04:42.320 --> 00:04:46.120
thing is that, except for a few pirates, all
of this trade was peaceful!

00:04:46.120 --> 00:04:49.880
For the better part of seven hundred years
these merchant ships were free to sail the

00:04:49.880 --> 00:04:52.740
seas without the need for protection from
any state’s navy. This despite the fact

00:04:52.740 --> 00:04:56.770
that some pretty valuable crap was being traded.
