welcomes a merchant -- and not just royalty.
The great thing about seaborne trade is that

00:06:16.950 --> 00:06:21.110
you can trade bulk goods like cotton cloth,
foodstuffs, and timber that’s all too heavy

00:06:21.110 --> 00:06:24.020
to strap onto a camel or mule. So for the
first time we see the beginnings of goods

00:06:24.020 --> 00:06:28.260
being traded for a mass market, instead of
just luxury goods, like silk for elites.

00:06:28.260 --> 00:06:31.650
Wood, for instance, can be used to build houses
-- but it’s not all that plentiful in the

00:06:31.650 --> 00:06:36.520
Arabian peninsula, however, when it becomes
cheaper thanks to trade, suddenly more people

00:06:36.520 --> 00:06:39.900
can have better houses. Much of the timber
that was shipped in the Monsoon Marketplace

00:06:39.900 --> 00:06:42.450
came from Africa, which is kind of emblematic.

00:06:42.450 --> 00:06:47.790
Africa produced a lot of the raw materials
like animal hides and skin and ivory and gold.

00:06:47.790 --> 00:06:51.760
The Swahili city states imported finished
goods such as silk and porcelain from China

00:06:51.760 --> 00:06:56.810
and cotton cloth from India. Spices and foodstuffs
like rice were shipped from Southeast Asia

00:06:56.810 --> 00:07:00.740
and especially Sri Lanka where black pepper
was a primary export good, and the Islamic

00:07:00.740 --> 00:07:04.710
world provided everything from coffee to books
and weapons. But it wasn’t just products

00:07:04.710 --> 00:07:07.900
that made their way around the eastern hemisphere
thanks to the Indian Ocean.

00:07:07.900 --> 00:07:10.870
Technology spread, too. Like the magnetic
compass, which is kind of crucial if you like

00:07:10.870 --> 00:07:14.540
to know where you’re going, came from China.
Muslim sailors popularized the astrolabe which

00:07:14.540 --> 00:07:18.770
made it easier to navigate by the stars. Boats
using stern-post rudders were easier to steer,

00:07:18.770 --> 00:07:21.870
so that technology quickly spread throughout
the Monsoon Marketplace. The Islamic world

00:07:21.870 --> 00:07:25.870
also produced the triangular lateen sail,
which became super important because it allowed

00:07:25.870 --> 00:07:28.919
for ships to tack against the wind. This meant
that a skilled crew could make their way through

00:07:28.919 --> 00:07:32.580
the ocean even if they didn’t have a strong
tailwind. And just as with the Silk Road,

00:07:32.580 --> 00:07:34.710
ideas also traveled in the Monsoon Marketplace.

00:07:34.710 --> 00:07:39.270
For instance today, more Muslims live in Indonesia
than in any other country. And yes, I know

00:07:39.270 --> 00:07:43.460
Indonesia has more than two islands. This
is not to scale, obviously. Knowing what you’ve

00:07:43.460 --> 00:07:46.510
already learned about the growth of Islam
and the spread of trade, it won’t surprise

00:07:46.510 --> 00:07:51.120
you to learn that Islam spread to Indonesia
via the Monsoon Marketplace. After the 1200s,

00:07:51.120 --> 00:07:54.550
the region which had previously been heavily
influenced by the Indian religions of Hinduism

00:07:54.550 --> 00:07:58.580
and Buddhism, like witness this temple, for
instance... became increasingly Islamic as

00:07:58.580 --> 00:08:03.300
rulers and elites adopted the religion so
they could have religious as well as economic

00:08:03.300 --> 00:08:06.479
ties to the people they were trading with.
The conversion of most of a region to Islam,

00:08:06.479 --> 00:08:09.850
where it continues to flourish today is a
pretty big deal. But Islam didn’t spread

00:08:09.850 --> 00:08:14.410
as effectively to the to Thailand, Laos, Cambodia
or Vietnam because they weren’t centers of trade.

00:08:14.410 --> 00:08:18.270
How do you become a center for trade? Well,
let’s zoom in here to the strait of Malacca.

00:08:18.270 --> 00:08:21.870
You can see how it could act as a choke point
for trade. Any city that controlled that strait

00:08:21.870 --> 00:08:25.740
could stop the ships from going through it,
or more likely tax them. And that’s exactly

00:08:25.740 --> 00:08:29.630
what happened, to such an extent that a powerful
merchant state called Srivijaya rose up on

00:08:29.630 --> 00:08:33.119
Sumatra. And for a while, Srivijaya dominated
trade in the region, because there were so

00:08:33.119 --> 00:08:37.240
many ships going through the Strait of Malacca
to and from China. But, as we’ll see in

00:08:37.240 --> 00:08:42.789
another episode that this trade abruptly declined
in the 15th century. And with it, so did Srivijaya.

00:08:42.789 --> 00:08:45.920
This brings up a key point about Indian Ocean
Trade, which is that it was indispensable

00:08:45.920 --> 00:08:49.949
to the creation of certain city states, like
Srivijaya and the city states of the Swahili

00:08:49.949 --> 00:08:54.840
Coast. Without trade, those places wouldn’t
have existed, let alone become wealthy and grand.

00:08:54.840 --> 00:08:57.980
Trade was a huge source of wealth for these
cities because they could tax it; through

00:08:57.980 --> 00:09:01.740
import and export duties or port fees. But
the fact that they are no longer powerful

00:09:01.740 --> 00:09:06.880
shows that trade can be a pretty weak foundation
on which to built a polity, even a small one.

00:09:06.880 --> 00:09:10.540
There are many reasons for this: like high
taxes can motivate traders to find other routes,

00:09:10.540 --> 00:09:14.740
for instance, but the main one is this: Reliance
upon trade makes you especially vulnerable

00:09:14.740 --> 00:09:18.540
to the peaks and troughs in the global economy.
The legacy of the merchant kingdom in Southeast

00:09:18.540 --> 00:09:22.019
Asia is still alive and well in Singapore,
for instance. But one of the great lessons

00:09:22.019 --> 00:09:26.350
of cities that have declined or disappeared
is that there’s usually a town nearby that’s

00:09:26.350 --> 00:09:30.829
eager to take your place and happy to offer
lower taxes. It’s almost as if the merchants

00:09:30.829 --> 00:09:34.990
decide where the people with the funny hats
go, rather than the other way around. Thanks

